82
00:04:30,274 --> 00:04:34,136
MultiBall is a mixtape of real multiplayer games from the 1980s and 90s.

83
00:04:34,256 --> 00:04:39,478
There have been projects in the past, like Rom Check Fail, or the Indie Pirate Cart,

84
00:04:39,498 --> 00:04:44,941
or WarioWare, that make a pastiche of multiple original games, but there's never been a collage

85
00:04:45,001 --> 00:04:49,103
made up of hundreds of existing games running on multiple hardware platforms.

86
00:04:50,538 --> 00:04:53,339
At its core, MultiBowl is a modified emulator.

87
00:04:53,780 --> 00:04:56,401
MAME, or the Multiple Arcade Machine Emulator,

88
00:04:56,521 --> 00:04:58,482
is the biggest and one of the oldest emulators

89
00:04:58,562 --> 00:05:00,423
on the planet, now 20 years old.

90
00:05:00,983 --> 00:05:03,165
It now emulates practically every arcade game

91
00:05:03,245 --> 00:05:05,666
and every console and computer platform from history.

92
00:05:06,166 --> 00:05:08,707
And last year, it switched to a proper open source license,

93
00:05:09,088 --> 00:05:10,789
so it became possible to think about projects

94
00:05:10,809 --> 00:05:13,010
that don't run on one hardware platform,

95
00:05:13,530 --> 00:05:15,071
but on all hardware platforms.

96
00:05:15,651 --> 00:05:17,832
Not one game, but all games.

97
00:05:18,753 --> 00:05:19,493
Here's how it works.

98
00:05:20,267 --> 00:05:24,632
It loads a random exciting moment from an old two-player game and lets you compete until

99
00:05:24,672 --> 00:05:28,435
someone scores a goal or kills the other player or until a timer runs out.

100
00:05:28,916 --> 00:05:33,400
By watching the memory in the emulated computer, it detects when someone wins the point and

101
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:35,502
loads another random moment from a random game.

102
00:05:37,424 --> 00:05:43,410
MultiBall now contains over 300 games across arcade platforms, consoles, and computers.

103
00:05:44,422 --> 00:05:48,165
And of course, there's way more than 300 good multiplayer games out there,

104
00:05:48,225 --> 00:05:53,249
but we tried to create a diverse list in terms of gameplay, art style, and country of origin.

105
00:05:54,030 --> 00:05:58,074
Each state is designed to run for about 30 seconds before it produces a win.

106
00:05:59,135 --> 00:06:01,537
So some games are just naturally perfect for that format.

107
00:06:02,117 --> 00:06:07,562
Outlaw is symmetrical and short, so we simply monitor the score and see who gets the first point.

108
00:06:09,085 --> 00:06:11,806
But some games need to be saved at a particular moment.

109
00:06:12,147 --> 00:06:14,868
For instance, after beating the final boss in Double Dragon,

110
00:06:15,088 --> 00:06:16,489
if both players are still alive,

111
00:06:16,529 --> 00:06:17,990
they then have to fight to decide

112
00:06:18,010 --> 00:06:19,871
who gets to rescue the red guy's girlfriend.

113
00:06:22,633 --> 00:06:24,134
In some cases, we change the rules

114
00:06:24,154 --> 00:06:25,375
to make a moment more exciting,

115
00:06:25,455 --> 00:06:28,177
as in this case, where the player's guns are disabled

116
00:06:28,277 --> 00:06:31,919
to turn Dodonpachi into a pure game of dodging.

117
00:06:37,300 --> 00:06:41,243
When you start playing MultiBowl, it's a pure test of video game talent.

118
00:06:41,743 --> 00:06:44,685
Who can figure out the mechanics and form strategies the fastest?

119
00:06:45,246 --> 00:06:50,710
Because it has a lot of lesser-known games, nobody has played the majority of them before.

120
00:06:54,413 --> 00:06:58,516
But once you've been playing for a while, it becomes more like a test of pure video

121
00:06:58,536 --> 00:06:59,156
game knowledge.

122
00:07:01,575 --> 00:07:06,701
Now, not every game lends itself well to competitive play, especially in 30-second slices.

123
00:07:07,162 --> 00:07:11,187
In Life Force, if you make the players compete for points, it's very hard to see whose bullets

124
00:07:11,227 --> 00:07:12,028
are hitting the enemies.

125
00:07:12,528 --> 00:07:14,771
And if you play to survive, it's just way too easy.

126
00:07:15,211 --> 00:07:18,896
Fundamentally, the problem is that each player can't affect the other player's performance.

127
00:07:20,567 --> 00:07:25,372
The solution we found to that is to have compound rules like score more points but don't die.

128
00:07:26,133 --> 00:07:31,059
So here a player can decide to be more aggressive, flying closer to the enemies, but that carries

129
00:07:31,119 --> 00:07:32,560
