00:33:46,907 --> 00:33:51,133
Last thing I want to say before we really get into it is that these games in no way

491
00:33:51,333 --> 00:33:59,206
obviously represent the totality of experimental gameplay in VR because all of VR is experimental.

492
00:34:01,150 --> 00:34:06,877
And I know that sounds like the ultimate soundbite from that hype train, and rest assured, it is.

493
00:34:07,557 --> 00:34:09,560
But I also think that there's some truth to it.

494
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:14,225
Games have had so long to develop, to build this universal vocabulary,

495
00:34:14,545 --> 00:34:18,029
that with our shared vernacular, we can describe these massive undertakings,

496
00:34:18,129 --> 00:34:21,152
these entire universes, with just three letters.

497
00:34:22,327 --> 00:34:28,810
Using terms like FPS, RPG, RTS, MMO, we have the ability to communicate so efficiently,

498
00:34:29,370 --> 00:34:34,092
so clearly, but these crystallized explanations leave little room for flexibility.

499
00:34:34,612 --> 00:34:37,013
They can be brittle, almost stifling.

500
00:34:37,954 --> 00:34:42,578
VR, obviously, on the other hand, doesn't have that much of a shared vocabulary yet.

501
00:34:43,199 --> 00:34:48,404
This means that it's tougher to describe a lot of the work, but with that ambiguity comes

502
00:34:48,505 --> 00:34:49,746
room to experiment.

503
00:34:50,807 --> 00:34:54,531
In a medium that doesn't even have a cohesive vision on what it means to move,

504
00:34:55,512 --> 00:34:58,294
Experimentation isn't just desirable, it is vital.

505
00:34:59,215 --> 00:35:03,219
It's a bit sad to see that already in this medium, which is so new,

506
00:35:03,259 --> 00:35:05,561
we see this tendency towards crystallization,

507
00:35:06,081 --> 00:35:08,484
the desire to use what has already been created

508
00:35:08,904 --> 00:35:12,107
instead of exploring and discovering what has never been,

509
00:35:12,127 --> 00:35:16,051
to manifest mechanics out of the ether.

510
00:35:17,395 --> 00:35:22,196
But even for games that tend towards the monolithic vocabulary, we see experimentation thrive.

511
00:35:23,277 --> 00:35:27,998
Take Cosmic Trip, which is made by a studio called Funktronic Labs, for example.

512
00:35:28,478 --> 00:35:35,521
This is a FPRTS, a first-person real-time strategy, which has a core loop that's extremely

513
00:35:35,561 --> 00:35:42,643
similar to a plethora of previous easily-definable experiences, Starcraft, Red Alert, etc.

514
00:35:43,143 --> 00:35:45,684
But it literally changes your perspective on RTSs.

515
00:35:46,524 --> 00:35:48,266
Take their menu system for example.

516
00:35:48,746 --> 00:35:52,790
UIs and menus in their current form are these displaced objects which are not part of the

517
00:35:52,830 --> 00:35:54,632
same universe as the rest of the game.

518
00:35:55,193 --> 00:35:59,657
But in Cosmic Trip, the menu has physicality, legitimate weight.

519
00:36:00,157 --> 00:36:05,522
Instead of falling into the rut of developmental efficiency, using the already normalized point

520
00:36:05,563 --> 00:36:10,788
and click of a brutally defined UI vocabulary, Funktronic took the time to explore.

521
00:36:12,205 --> 00:36:16,346
It's the same thing with their teleportation system, and movement is something that VR

522
00:36:16,386 --> 00:36:17,766
has been struggling with for a while.

523
00:36:18,346 --> 00:36:22,727
Rather than the typical ballistics which so many games now unceremoniously implement,

524
00:36:23,108 --> 00:36:25,488
they built this unique system that would fit their game.

525
00:36:25,948 --> 00:36:30,710
By pulling up the columns and stepping through them, they created a cohesive world that was

526
00:36:30,790 --> 00:36:35,311
so different from any before it, it became hard to describe using the current vocabulary.

527
00:36:36,453 --> 00:36:42,097
It may be that in the distant future, this weighty user interface, or possibly the column

528
00:36:42,157 --> 00:36:47,842
transportation system, might become one of the TLAs, three-letter acronyms, that we will

529
00:36:47,922 --> 00:36:52,685
all know and love, but it will be because of those brave possibility space explorers

530
00:36:52,825 --> 00:36:58,850
over at Funktronic Labs, and many other studios went out and tried word after word after word

531
00:36:58,910 --> 00:37:02,973
until a few finally made sense, and they could let us experience the thrill of

532
00:37:03,694 --> 00:37:06,316
of understanding something for the first time.

533
00:37:07,917 --> 00:37:09,518
And I think that's why a lot of us are here.

534
00:37:10,359 --> 00:37:15,403
That moment where we get to grok one of those untranslatable words, and it becomes part

535
00:37:15,424 --> 00:37:17,806
of our vocabulary, part of our reality.

536
00:37:18,466 --> 00:37:22,930
Games have an inherent ability to do this, to take the unfamiliar and make it familiar,

537
00:37:23,410 --> 00:37:27,974
to take the unknown and make it known, and has been doing so since its beginning.

538
00:37:28,615 --> 00:37:35,082
Tetris, Pong, Breakout were all once unfamiliar, but once played and understood, they become

539
00:37:35,223 --> 00:37:39,407
part of the vocabulary, transitioned from experimental to canonical.

540
00:37:40,048 --> 00:37:42,030
They created a word.

541
00:37:43,052 --> 00:37:45,034
And this wordsmithing is everywhere in VR.

542
00:37:45,114 --> 00:37:47,597
Even I tried to do it myself and also came up with a word.

543
00:37:48,398 --> 00:37:48,658
Blarp.

544
00:37:50,808 --> 00:37:55,815
Now, its gameplay is only as deep as its name and its artistic polish is, you know, equally

545
00:37:55,875 --> 00:38:00,520
amateur, but I can safely say that there are no TLAs that describe its mechanics.

546
00:38:01,061 --> 00:38:05,767
I've tried describing how it works and I actually fail quite often, so I wanted to let some

547
00:38:05,787 --> 00:38:08,010
of the reviews from Steam try to do the same.

548
00:38:09,307 --> 00:38:14,308
As Person Guy says, you spin these things above your head like a stretchy lasso and

549
00:38:14,328 --> 00:38:16,069
try to toss them at a randomized target.

550
00:38:17,009 --> 00:38:22,331
Bassem, on the other hand, argues, you corral an ever-growing number of floating eyeballs

551
00:38:22,391 --> 00:38:26,653
in an ever-growing room, twirling them around like bolas or a bunch of yo-yos.

552
00:38:27,613 --> 00:38:30,654
Perhaps the most articulate is Seibert, who claims,

553
00:38:31,335 --> 00:38:34,896
Blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp, blarp,

554
00:38:34,916 --> 00:38:35,876
blarp, blarp.

555
00:38:36,897 --> 00:38:38,137
Couldn't have said it better myself.

556
00:38:39,571 --> 00:38:44,452
But blarp is confusing to describe because it wasn't a word that could exist before VR.

557
00:38:45,032 --> 00:38:48,833
It requires a room-scale HMD to be able to quickly spin and dodge.

558
00:38:49,193 --> 00:38:54,695
It would be impossible without hand controllers to pull the floating eyeballs on that stretchy lasso.

559
00:38:55,375 --> 00:39:03,057
And without the floating point trigger, you couldn't be so delicate, twirling and spinning in some ritualistic dance of cord-tangling delight.

560
00:39:04,698 --> 00:39:08,562
This is not, of course, to say that Blarp will become a classic like Tetris or Pong.

561
00:39:09,523 --> 00:39:15,469
On the contrary, it is the unfortunate fact that many experimental games never become

562
00:39:15,550 --> 00:39:20,315
part of the vocabulary because they are ignored, or even worse, because they might get attention

563
00:39:20,335 --> 00:39:23,618
but are considered too far out for popular consumption.

564
00:39:26,163 --> 00:39:28,966
Besides, blarp isn't a very good word.

565
00:39:29,587 --> 00:39:32,570
It might be fun to say, goofy and non-assuming.

566
00:39:32,890 --> 00:39:35,753
But in the end, the thing that it is pulling from the ether,

567
00:39:36,254 --> 00:39:38,256
though a novel mechanic, doesn't really

568
00:39:38,396 --> 00:39:40,278
say anything that could not be said before.

569
00:39:41,059 --> 00:39:43,161
It's just creating a new mode of entertainment.

570
00:39:43,862 --> 00:39:48,466
It's just making another feedback loop that scratches that itch of scoring a point, scoring

571
00:39:48,506 --> 00:39:52,990
another point, losing and starting over again, knowing that this time, this time will be

572
00:39:53,030 --> 00:39:56,153
the time that I win and prove my worth with quantified score.

573
00:39:58,276 --> 00:40:00,777
But there are other words out there, difficult words,

574
00:40:00,817 --> 00:40:02,939
that try and say delicate things,

575
00:40:03,339 --> 00:40:04,800
that try to describe emotions

576
00:40:04,840 --> 00:40:07,221
that might have been impossible to describe before.

577
00:40:08,301 --> 00:40:10,823
Take Nebula Hands, which is a prototype

578
00:40:10,863 --> 00:40:12,364
that Mike Tucker has been working on.

579
00:40:12,824 --> 00:40:14,805
It lets you be alone in the darkness,

580
00:40:15,325 --> 00:40:17,607
exploring the physics of these tiny particles,

581
00:40:18,007 --> 00:40:20,108
letting you feel like a solitary god

582
00:40:20,188 --> 00:40:23,110
witnessing the sparkling, iridescent light in the abyss.

583
00:40:24,290 --> 00:40:26,311
Or Cave Carver by Fernando Romero.

584
00:40:27,531 --> 00:40:31,193
where you slowly sculpt away layers of your cocoon

585
00:40:31,293 --> 00:40:33,994
until you discover the infinity in which you reside.

586
00:40:35,175 --> 00:40:37,536
Or Irrational Exuberance, the first VR piece

587
00:40:37,616 --> 00:40:38,396
that made me cry.

588
00:40:39,837 --> 00:40:41,538
In it, you travel through this universe,

589
00:40:41,718 --> 00:40:43,859
gently tapping rocks to reveal secrets,

590
00:40:44,359 --> 00:40:46,040
and as they crumble on your hands,

591
00:40:46,080 --> 00:40:48,201
you sense this feeling of time passing,

592
00:40:48,701 --> 00:40:50,482
a sunset that must dissipate.

593
00:40:51,455 --> 00:40:54,117
You grow crystals, the sounds tickling your ears,

594
00:40:54,197 --> 00:40:57,859
as you marvel at your ability to create and to wreck conversation

595
00:40:57,899 --> 00:41:00,680
with your entropy-based destruction of the level before.

596
00:41:02,281 --> 00:41:07,224
It's mysterious, ambiguous, paradoxical, and also delightful.

597
00:41:09,265 --> 00:41:11,146
As usual, the Steam reviews show it.

598
00:41:12,107 --> 00:41:18,310
MetaVisual says, this is, there aren't really words.

599
00:41:18,790 --> 00:41:20,531
It's beautiful, existential.

600
00:41:22,215 --> 00:41:25,981
And I know that Steam reviews are a bit of a silly way to prove a point, because some

601
00:41:26,021 --> 00:41:32,091
of them are equally as banal as the above was poetic, such as this one, which I got

602
00:41:32,131 --> 00:41:32,652
for Loon.

603
00:41:33,853 --> 00:41:35,716
Amusing and neat for about 10 minutes.

604
00:41:36,417 --> 00:41:37,319
Not recommended.

605
00:41:39,363 --> 00:41:44,386
Loon, a accidental creation that came from trying to implement a GPU-based cloth sim,

606
00:41:44,946 --> 00:41:49,469
is an architectural haiku whose thesis is very difficult for me to describe.

607
00:41:50,089 --> 00:41:55,272
It's the only thing in VR which I have made which I know says a word that matters.

608
00:41:56,823 --> 00:42:00,125
But it is a word that requires somebody quietly and calmly

609
00:42:00,205 --> 00:42:01,465
going through the experience.

610
00:42:02,046 --> 00:42:04,107
I tried it myself and felt that emotion,

611
00:42:04,467 --> 00:42:06,028
but didn't know how to communicate it

612
00:42:06,368 --> 00:42:10,130
and what it even meant until I read this review by 60FPS.

613
00:42:11,971 --> 00:42:14,433
I was a sobbing mess, muttering to myself alone

614
00:42:14,473 --> 00:42:16,034
in the bathroom mirror in disbelief

615
00:42:16,074 --> 00:42:19,116
at how squarely this dev had hit a certain emotional nail

616
00:42:19,196 --> 00:42:22,758
on the head, the tritone nail of beauty, awe,

617
00:42:23,158 --> 00:42:24,018
and boundless love.

618
00:42:25,662 --> 00:42:28,163
And I say this not just to flaunt my own ego,

619
00:42:28,523 --> 00:42:30,064
even though it is the best compliment

620
00:42:30,104 --> 00:42:32,264
that I will probably ever receive,

621
00:42:32,744 --> 00:42:36,065
but more to say that it is okay to try and say these words,

622
00:42:36,806 --> 00:42:39,226
even if we fail at saying them in the process.

623
00:42:40,086 --> 00:42:41,407
The attempt to say a new word

624
00:42:41,447 --> 00:42:43,728
will many times result in gibberish,

625
00:42:43,848 --> 00:42:47,029
like blarp or warka-flarka-flim-flam.

626
00:42:47,949 --> 00:42:51,010
But when we find something that can say something more,

627
00:42:51,150 --> 00:42:52,370
we must try to say it.

628
00:42:53,445 --> 00:42:58,347
I believe that people are hungry, not just for novel mechanics, but for those novel mechanics

629
00:42:58,407 --> 00:42:59,707
to say something else.

630
00:43:00,348 --> 00:43:05,310
To make us remember that our reality is so much more than we thought was possible before.

631
00:43:07,205 --> 00:43:10,168
that in a place where no word has ever touched,

632
00:43:10,549 --> 00:43:11,370
there lies meaning.

633
00:43:12,290 --> 00:43:15,093
And I want to very, very, very adamantly add

634
00:43:15,133 --> 00:43:17,055
that this is not unique to VR,

635
00:43:17,536 --> 00:43:20,158
but I can already see the same pattern emerging

636
00:43:20,499 --> 00:43:24,102
where so many tender and nuanced emotions are explored,

637
00:43:24,503 --> 00:43:26,325
but only the ones that are catchy

638
00:43:26,485 --> 00:43:28,206
or palpable enough rise to the top.

639
00:43:29,855 --> 00:43:33,977
This is not to say that those games have, those catchy games have any less importance.

640
00:43:34,497 --> 00:43:38,700
I really, really, really do love Blarp and I really, really do love catchy games.

641
00:43:39,240 --> 00:43:43,903
But rather that exploration must be valued at its core.

642
00:43:44,603 --> 00:43:45,964
I don't know exactly what...

643
00:43:46,664 --> 00:43:49,345
attaining this value looks like. It could be something like

644
00:43:50,126 --> 00:43:55,548
the stuff that David Kanaga has been talking about with the GPU. It could be something else totally different.

645
00:43:56,008 --> 00:44:01,951
But the point is not just to be trying to find these new places, these new places,

646
00:44:02,511 --> 00:44:09,935
these new games, these new planets that have unobtainium or platinum ore, but to explore because that curiosity,

647
00:44:10,515 --> 00:44:14,096
that desire to expand the understanding of the worlds we live in,

648
00:44:14,877 --> 00:44:17,257
is a big part of what makes us human.

649
00:44:19,538 --> 00:44:22,819
Because in the end, I hope that we are not exploring

650
00:44:22,959 --> 00:44:24,559
just to find the palpable words

651
00:44:24,659 --> 00:44:26,280
that can be financially successful,

652
00:44:26,860 --> 00:44:30,121
to make games that will be considered PCE,

653
00:44:31,581 --> 00:44:35,242
but rather to acknowledge that we, as creators,

654
00:44:35,662 --> 00:44:38,543
have the ability to find new words

655
00:44:38,643 --> 00:44:42,084
that shape the very language we use to describe our reality.

656
00:44:43,099 --> 00:44:46,465
And with that description, we define that reality.

657
00:44:47,147 --> 00:44:47,527
Thank you.

658
00:44:52,697 --> 00:44:53,158
Awesome.

659
00:44:54,000 --> 00:44:54,461
Woo!

660
00:44:54,641 --> 00:44:54,962
All right.

661
00:44:57,212 --> 00:45:02,154
So as he mentioned, there will be games up here at the front of the session when the session is over.

662
00:45:02,975 --> 00:45:06,616
And there will be games that you can play physically with your body,

663
00:45:06,936 --> 00:45:13,059
which is hopefully not in as rough shape as mine is after four nights of three hours of sleep.

664
00:45:14,560 --> 00:45:22,143
And so next up, we actually have Bastien Gorisson and Pauline Morillet to talk about

665
00:45:22,163 --> 00:45:24,484
Panoptic.

666
00:45:33,743 --> 00:45:37,484
Hi everyone, we are part of Team Panoptes and we are making Panoptique.

667
00:45:38,185 --> 00:45:41,106
My name is Pauline Marrière and I am the Art Director of the game.

668
00:45:41,566 --> 00:45:44,688
For the purpose of the presentation, I'll be inside the VR headset.

669
00:45:45,741 --> 00:45:49,905
Hi, I'm Bastien, I'm one of the designer, developers and I'm the composer for the game.

670
00:45:50,326 --> 00:45:51,947
And so, what is Panoptic?

671
00:45:52,688 --> 00:45:58,234
Well, it's an asymmetrical VR game in which a small character, played by me here on this laptop,

672
00:45:58,514 --> 00:46:02,078
has to avoid detection by the huge mask that you see in the sky,

673
00:46:02,198 --> 00:46:04,881
and that's played by Pauline using the VR headset.

674
00:46:06,393 --> 00:46:12,757
So my goal is to reach the end of the level without getting shot by the Overseer, while

675
00:46:12,857 --> 00:46:18,301
of course her goal will be to find where I am in the level and just shoot me down before

676
00:46:18,341 --> 00:46:19,101
I reach that goal.

677
00:46:19,642 --> 00:46:22,944
So it's really some kind of hide and seek game.

678
00:46:23,844 --> 00:46:30,272
in which I have several options. I can take it very careful and slow and be methodical and try to blend in with

679
00:46:30,412 --> 00:46:38,262
all these little guys that look exactly like me or I can just break into a run and try to use like jumping and

680
00:46:38,823 --> 00:46:40,084
sprinting to avoid

681
00:46:40,845 --> 00:46:42,648
the shots from the overseer.

682
00:46:43,853 --> 00:46:50,678
So, as you see, the core gameplay is very simple, but we did have to iterate quite a bit to get to where we are now.

683
00:46:51,059 --> 00:46:56,163
And we are actually still finding out some of the things that make the game design click.

684
00:46:56,723 --> 00:47:02,528
One thing that's fairly evident, and that was fairly obvious from a while ago,

685
00:47:02,848 --> 00:47:06,551
was that the game is at its most fun when the two players are interacting.

686
00:47:06,992 --> 00:47:11,775
When the VR player is really hot on the heels of the PC player and...

687
00:47:12,636 --> 00:47:17,183
where there's real tension in all the moves you do as the PC player.

688
00:47:17,624 --> 00:47:21,370
So that's really one of our main goals in the game,

689
00:47:21,390 --> 00:47:26,658
is to provide those kind of situations and improve the time both players spend.

690
00:47:27,819 --> 00:47:29,802
on each other's heels.

691
00:47:30,663 --> 00:47:34,027
But to show you how we arrived at that point,

692
00:47:34,047 --> 00:47:36,109
let me take you back to the very beginning.

693
00:47:36,730 --> 00:47:40,274
So we started by testing out the basic concept of the game.

694
00:47:41,034 --> 00:47:43,557
So basically, we had a regular-sized player,

695
00:47:44,458 --> 00:47:47,702
and we just scaled up the VR person like 30 times.

696
00:47:49,624 --> 00:47:58,990
We spent way too much time doing just that, like picking up the player and trying to get him to stay on the controllers and preventing him to fall.

697
00:48:00,711 --> 00:48:03,233
You're not getting away, you know.

698
00:48:03,893 --> 00:48:10,237
Obviously not, because when you're so big in VR, your hands move way too quickly for the PC player to ever compete.

699
00:48:10,758 --> 00:48:18,303
So basically we decided that that was maybe a bit too overpowered and that was probably out as a way of interacting between the players.

700
00:48:19,804 --> 00:48:22,906
But of course, you still needed a way to stop the challenger

701
00:48:23,006 --> 00:48:24,347
from reaching his goal.

702
00:48:24,688 --> 00:48:28,490
So we were thinking about what's really fun about the game.

703
00:48:28,891 --> 00:48:31,773
And we found out that actually just looking around

704
00:48:32,253 --> 00:48:33,554
was a lot of fun.

705
00:48:33,574 --> 00:48:35,556
You have all these small structures,

706
00:48:35,616 --> 00:48:37,697
and you see the little character and all that.

707
00:48:37,737 --> 00:48:40,399
And it's a bit like when you look at a model train or Legos

708
00:48:40,519 --> 00:48:41,680
or dollhouses.

709
00:48:42,281 --> 00:48:45,445
stuff that people like to examine. So we said, okay, we might like

710
00:48:45,766 --> 00:48:47,929
find something to work with in that.

711
00:48:48,410 --> 00:48:53,017
And we said, okay, what if you could shoot a laser from where you are looking at?

712
00:48:53,996 --> 00:48:55,977
fell straight forward, and so we went with that.

713
00:48:56,518 --> 00:49:00,560
And almost immediately, we knew that there was no avoiding

714
00:49:00,580 --> 00:49:02,401
a comparison to like Lord of the Rings

715
00:49:02,461 --> 00:49:04,163
and the Eye of Sauron kind of deal.

716
00:49:04,523 --> 00:49:06,204
So instead of trying to dodge that

717
00:49:06,284 --> 00:49:08,906
and be like all artsy about it, we just owned it.

718
00:49:09,406 --> 00:49:13,409
And we put as a visual feedback for the overseer,

719
00:49:13,429 --> 00:49:17,511
