to coordinate how they're going to overcome these different environmental obstacles.

957
01:07:32,059 --> 01:07:40,122
As the game goes on, they're given new abilities that allow them to change the properties of the triangles that make up their character forms

958
01:07:40,522 --> 01:07:43,463
and have effect on the triangles surrounding them in the world.

959
01:07:44,564 --> 01:07:49,666
These abilities progress as the game goes on in power, but also in abstraction.

960
01:07:53,677 --> 01:07:55,258
And then as the gameplay becomes harder,

961
01:07:55,278 --> 01:07:56,919
the two players really have to coordinate

962
01:07:56,959 --> 01:07:58,240
these abilities to advance.

963
01:07:59,100 --> 01:08:00,961
There are, we had to build a number

964
01:08:00,982 --> 01:08:03,123
of different environmental levels, you see some here,

965
01:08:03,403 --> 01:08:05,264
just as prototype beds to be able to sort of,

966
01:08:05,344 --> 01:08:06,625
you know, flesh out the look of the game,

967
01:08:06,845 --> 01:08:09,227
but also experiment with the combinatorial aspects

968
01:08:09,247 --> 01:08:11,248
of these abilities to yield mechanics.

969
01:08:11,409 --> 01:08:12,970
And what I, you know, in demos,

970
01:08:13,010 --> 01:08:14,831
we were really seeing a lot of emergent gameplay.

971
01:08:22,830 --> 01:08:24,431
There's a moment that we haven't built yet

972
01:08:24,552 --> 01:08:25,512
in the future of the game,

973
01:08:26,053 --> 01:08:28,574
where the item that grants the abilities and powers

974
01:08:28,615 --> 01:08:29,595
to the players breaks,

975
01:08:29,956 --> 01:08:33,398
and force them to adjust to a new level of abstraction.

976
01:08:34,279 --> 01:08:36,440
The character forms end up breaking down completely,

977
01:08:36,780 --> 01:08:38,282
and although the game responds to input,

978
01:08:38,442 --> 01:08:40,483
it might not be in ways that are completely expected.

979
01:08:41,304 --> 01:08:42,004
After this moment,

980
01:08:42,064 --> 01:08:43,705
the players have to deliberately restore

981
01:08:43,726 --> 01:08:45,026
a degree of order to the world.

982
01:08:46,377 --> 01:08:47,918
On the audio side, as an audio person,

983
01:08:47,938 --> 01:08:50,059
I was always working with Roger to try to explore

984
01:08:50,099 --> 01:08:52,921
some audio aspects of doing the same thing.

985
01:08:52,961 --> 01:08:54,682
And so we had come up with this great system

986
01:08:54,722 --> 01:08:56,763
that I was really looking forward to implement,

987
01:08:56,843 --> 01:08:58,705
and hopefully we will in the future of the game,

988
01:08:59,005 --> 01:09:02,287
which would be the ability to both de-res the audio,

989
01:09:02,367 --> 01:09:04,448
basically fracture the audio in real time,

990
01:09:04,508 --> 01:09:07,049
scaling it from full fidelity all the way down

991
01:09:07,830 --> 01:09:11,512
to highly compressed and thereby very artifacted sounding

992
01:09:12,092 --> 01:09:14,154
to sort of play along with the same scaling up

993
01:09:14,194 --> 01:09:15,675
and scaling down of the triangle system.

994
01:09:21,979 --> 01:09:27,801
So, just before the end of 2016, we had finished our first vertical slice and began working

995
01:09:27,821 --> 01:09:29,461
on the horizontal slice of the game.

996
01:09:30,001 --> 01:09:34,803
But then the sudden passing of Roger in January, obviously, has halted our progress.

997
01:09:35,003 --> 01:09:40,244
And so, we're currently working through all the emotions to be surrounded by such an amazing

998
01:09:40,284 --> 01:09:41,145
community of gamers.

999
01:09:41,805 --> 01:09:48,167
who have supported him has been really amazing. And Anita and I and those close to Roger are

1000
01:09:48,287 --> 01:09:53,049
extremely passionate about the future of Shard. And so Anita?

1001
01:09:53,990 --> 01:09:58,412
Our goal is that in a few months we'll be able to formulate a plan on how we can complete and

1002
01:09:58,432 --> 01:10:05,254
release Shard in a way that honors Roger's legacy. So until then, here's some ways you can

1003
01:10:05,294 --> 01:10:10,657
continue to follow us online. Thanks so much to the whole EGW team.

1004
01:10:11,244 --> 01:10:16,808
and especially to San Francisco indie developers for your support. I want to leave you with a

1005
01:10:16,888 --> 01:10:23,613
quote from Roger, which he once wrote in response to the question, why do you play games? If

1006
01:10:23,633 --> 01:10:28,536
something can be imagined, it can be created in a video game. In that regard, that's the

1007
01:10:28,596 --> 01:10:34,201
ultimate form of freedom of expression of ideas. And games today touch on a large gamut of

1008
01:10:34,261 --> 01:10:34,401
that.

1009
01:10:35,423 --> 01:10:44,711
dread, euphoria, desire, fear, rage, compassion, order, chaos, logic, beauty in all its forms.

1010
01:10:46,292 --> 01:10:46,532
Thanks.

1011
01:11:10,654 --> 01:11:14,895
I just wanted to take a moment and acknowledge the fact that the community came together

1012
01:11:15,495 --> 01:11:20,716
very well and in a great, amazing, loving moment when Roger passed.

1013
01:11:21,256 --> 01:11:25,017
It was his dream to present this game here and to be able to do that is one of the greatest

1014
01:11:25,077 --> 01:11:26,057
things of my life.

1015
01:11:26,658 --> 01:11:29,658
It's my greatest regret that he didn't live to see this moment.

1016
01:11:29,878 --> 01:11:32,479
I just wanted to say that he loved you all very, very much.

1017
01:11:32,999 --> 01:11:33,399
Thank you.

1018
01:11:44,945 --> 01:11:49,801
And with that, one of my most favorite people, Jen Sandercock and Josh are here to show us Edible Games.

1019
01:11:57,007 --> 01:11:59,868
All right, hi everyone, I'm Jen Sandercock,

1020
01:12:00,308 --> 01:12:01,448
and I'm talking about edible games.

1021
01:12:02,529 --> 01:12:03,189
What do I mean?

1022
01:12:03,809 --> 01:12:07,751
I mean games where one of the core gameplay mechanics is eating.

1023
01:12:08,451 --> 01:12:09,891
And I'm not talking about food as a reward,

1024
01:12:09,951 --> 01:12:14,353
I'm talking about like somehow eating changes the games somehow.

1025
01:12:14,753 --> 01:12:15,673
Why am I doing this?

1026
01:12:15,873 --> 01:12:17,374
I'm doing this because I love to bake,

1027
01:12:18,314 --> 01:12:20,135
I really like real world games,

1028
01:12:21,235 --> 01:12:23,016
and I like designing games.

1029
01:12:23,216 --> 01:12:25,877
This is a bunch of games that I've worked on over the years.

1030
01:12:27,460 --> 01:12:30,343
So by my powers combined, yay, edible games.

1031
01:12:32,265 --> 01:12:34,408
So in the beginning, one of the first games I did

1032
01:12:34,428 --> 01:12:35,709
was called the cookie baking game.

1033
01:12:36,550 --> 01:12:38,893
In the cookie baking game, you compete for ingredients

1034
01:12:38,993 --> 01:12:40,555
and then you eat the cookies that you bake

1035
01:12:40,575 --> 01:12:41,496
at the end as a reward.

1036
01:12:44,164 --> 01:12:48,325
But the thing was, the gameplay was kind of little mini-games to compete for the ingredients

1037
01:12:48,365 --> 01:12:51,746
and you didn't really interact with the food particularly much and it wasn't really cohesive

1038
01:12:51,786 --> 01:12:52,126
as a whole.

1039
01:12:52,606 --> 01:12:58,968
So the big question I needed to ask was, what new gameplay mechanics are only possible with

1040
01:12:59,048 --> 01:13:01,668
edible games and cannot be done with any other type of game?

1041
01:13:02,208 --> 01:13:04,389
Basically I was asking, what does food give us?

1042
01:13:05,129 --> 01:13:09,810
Food gives us a bunch of societal norms, hidden information with your taste buds, allergies,

1043
01:13:09,890 --> 01:13:13,311
personal preference, they're messy, germs, all of these things.

1044
01:13:14,151 --> 01:13:17,612
So because I'm doing a series of games, I'm going to talk to you about six of the games

1045
01:13:17,672 --> 01:13:20,013
that I've got that I think are pretty solid right now.

1046
01:13:20,814 --> 01:13:23,315
So the first one is Gingerbread Friends.

1047
01:13:23,775 --> 01:13:27,416
Gingerbread Friends is set up with a board with lids on top.

1048
01:13:27,496 --> 01:13:29,597
It's a slow game about making friends.

1049
01:13:30,037 --> 01:13:33,798
There are hidden prizes inside, which are the gummy bears, and then there are also pieces

1050
01:13:33,858 --> 01:13:34,339
of paper.

1051
01:13:34,779 --> 01:13:38,280
The pieces of paper are Minesweeper-like and tell you where to find a gummy bear.

1052
01:13:39,120 --> 01:13:43,903
You earn the right to eat a lid by guessing others' answers to social questions.

1053
01:13:44,384 --> 01:13:47,706
So, for example, when it's your turn, you might ask the group,

1054
01:13:48,865 --> 01:13:53,806
Would it be a relief to realize you were ordinary, no better or worse than most others?

1055
01:13:54,466 --> 01:13:58,087
And then you guess if everybody will say yes or no and then you might get a lid.

1056
01:13:59,028 --> 01:14:00,408
Next game, Master Taster.

1057
01:14:00,468 --> 01:14:03,169
In Master Taster, it's about memory and taste buds.

1058
01:14:03,469 --> 01:14:08,070
There are a series of rounds and in each round you find out the taste preferences of the

1059
01:14:08,110 --> 01:14:09,270
two main characters.

1060
01:14:09,791 --> 01:14:12,731
Then you must eat one of the items with your eyes closed.

1061
01:14:13,552 --> 01:14:16,496
As you're eating it, you need to work out what flavour that is.

1062
01:14:16,796 --> 01:14:18,798
And it might be a combination of flavours too.

1063
01:14:19,359 --> 01:14:21,762
You then say whether the characters can or can't eat it

1064
01:14:21,782 --> 01:14:23,565
by putting thumbs up or thumbs down.

1065
01:14:24,045 --> 01:14:25,747
If you're correct, you stay in the game.

1066
01:14:26,228 --> 01:14:29,853
Information is never repeated, and information builds every single round.

1067
01:14:30,734 --> 01:14:32,335
Next game, Flavour Roulette.

1068
01:14:32,495 --> 01:14:35,978
In Flavour Roulette, there are four players with four morsels.

1069
01:14:36,178 --> 01:14:37,979
One of these does not taste like the others.

1070
01:14:38,099 --> 01:14:39,480
It's probably pretty gross.

1071
01:14:40,621 --> 01:14:44,864
You take turns eating, and then you have to pretend like yours is normal.

1072
01:14:44,924 --> 01:14:46,445
So this is my friend Owen here.

1073
01:14:47,706 --> 01:14:53,211
So, would you believe he actually has a normal one?

1074
01:14:53,231 --> 01:14:55,833
He's trying to convince everybody that they should vote for him.

1075
01:14:57,670 --> 01:15:01,014
So once everybody's eaten, you then guess who had the bad one.

1076
01:15:02,416 --> 01:15:04,058
The next game is Flip and Stick.

1077
01:15:04,118 --> 01:15:07,602
In Flip and Stick, there are a grid of peanut butter covered crackers.

1078
01:15:07,963 --> 01:15:12,248
You choose a square to hit, for example, D5, and you try to aim for it and hit.

1079
01:15:13,185 --> 01:15:16,550
If you miss, there are more points for everyone else and slash chocolate.

1080
01:15:17,491 --> 01:15:21,938
And if you hit it, you need to flip upside down your square and see what sticks.

1081
01:15:22,198 --> 01:15:25,122
You get as many points as whatever sticks to your square.

1082
01:15:25,583 --> 01:15:28,627
And then you get to like throw a bunch of chocolate at the table so that there's more

1083
01:15:28,667 --> 01:15:29,408
points for everyone.

1084
01:15:31,301 --> 01:15:35,004
The next game is called J-Wobbler, and this is a tray

1085
01:15:35,304 --> 01:15:37,506
of what I call jelly, you guys call Jello.

1086
01:15:37,926 --> 01:15:40,588
With gummy bears hidden inside, you have 10 seconds to try

1087
01:15:40,628 --> 01:15:42,790
to wobble to get the jawbreaker to land on top

1088
01:15:42,830 --> 01:15:43,731
of one of the gummy bears.

1089
01:15:44,171 --> 01:15:46,453
If it does, you then get to eat the square.

1090
01:15:47,714 --> 01:15:49,215
Now there's a big hole in the board

1091
01:15:49,415 --> 01:15:51,497
which your jawbreaker is very likely to fall into.

1092
01:15:52,663 --> 01:15:56,452
So I'm going to now do a deep dive on a game called The Order of the Oven Mitt.

1093
01:15:56,953 --> 01:16:01,303
The tagline is, do you have the appetite to join the Knights of the Oven Mitt?

1094
01:16:02,521 --> 01:16:06,763
I did this for the Global Game Jam in 2016, where the theme was ritual.

1095
01:16:07,163 --> 01:16:11,025
I did a bunch of failed prototypes where there was too much thinking, not enough fun, and

1096
01:16:11,125 --> 01:16:12,385
definitely not enough eating.

1097
01:16:13,566 --> 01:16:17,708
It's a two-team game, and you move just like a chess knight on the board, so in an L shape.

1098
01:16:18,728 --> 01:16:22,770
There are two types of squares, the sacred squares, which are the dark squares, and the

1099
01:16:22,810 --> 01:16:24,631
common squares, which are the light squares.

1100
01:16:26,272 --> 01:16:30,934
If you land on a sacred square, you must consume it according to the sacred ritual as laid

1101
01:16:32,609 --> 01:16:34,149
the sacred tomb of the oven mitt.

1102
01:16:35,890 --> 01:16:38,651
This is what some of the rituals look like.

1103
01:16:39,731 --> 01:16:41,271
Once you have consumed that square,

1104
01:16:41,291 --> 01:16:43,052
you then have a hole on the board.

1105
01:16:43,352 --> 01:16:44,672
And you can't stand on top of a hole,

1106
01:16:44,732 --> 01:16:47,253
so you have to push the squares around.

1107
01:16:47,673 --> 01:16:48,753
That might push you.

1108
01:16:48,853 --> 01:16:50,673
It might move the other player as well.

1109
01:16:51,213 --> 01:16:54,714
And it will mean that perhaps the other player might not

1110
01:16:54,734 --> 01:16:56,175
be able to get the candy you like.

1111
01:16:57,716 --> 01:17:02,458
If you land on one of the common squares, you can't eat the common squares because that will sully you.

1112
01:17:03,378 --> 01:17:06,159
So the game is over when all of the sacred squares have been eaten.

1113
01:17:07,880 --> 01:17:12,641
The rituals are really a fun performance for players and observers.

1114
01:17:12,981 --> 01:17:15,742
It's creating a sacred space where you're allowed to be totally silly.

1115
01:17:16,803 --> 01:17:21,785
The initial feedback I got on the game was that I could push the rituals to make them even more embarrassing for people.

1116
01:17:23,359 --> 01:17:26,181
There's kind of two different sorts of play styles that you can play.

1117
01:17:26,601 --> 01:17:30,304
Because the game itself doesn't really care who eats the sacred squares, they just have

1118
01:17:30,344 --> 01:17:30,884
to be eaten.

1119
01:17:31,164 --> 01:17:35,467
You can either compete to see who gets the most or cooperate and help each other both

1120
01:17:35,507 --> 01:17:36,628
get the squares that you want.

1121
01:17:37,348 --> 01:17:40,471
There are unique play strategies because people have food preferences.

1122
01:17:40,871 --> 01:17:43,012
So for example, this is a Reese's Peanut Butter Cup.

1123
01:17:43,352 --> 01:17:44,633
Many people like these.

1124
01:17:46,114 --> 01:17:48,417
Some people don't, but if you're both like them,

1125
01:17:48,438 --> 01:17:49,860
you might compete for them and go,

1126
01:17:49,900 --> 01:17:51,482
hey, I'm gonna not let you have that.

1127
01:17:51,802 --> 01:17:55,187
But you might go, ooh, if I let you have the jelly beans,

1128
01:17:55,207 --> 01:17:57,090
will you let me have the Reese's Peanut Butter Cup?

1129
01:17:58,662 --> 01:18:00,983
There are unique challenges for demoing this.

1130
01:18:01,063 --> 01:18:02,824
I've showed it at IndieCade last year,

1131
01:18:02,884 --> 01:18:04,065
and I spent days baking.

1132
01:18:04,105 --> 01:18:06,466
I had an army of helpers helping me.

1133
01:18:06,606 --> 01:18:07,287
It was amazing.

1134
01:18:08,067 --> 01:18:11,049
I'm now going to try to do a live example.

1135
01:18:11,069 --> 01:18:12,609
So we're gonna switch to, I've got a camera,

1136
01:18:12,950 --> 01:18:16,631
and I have some volunteers over here.

1137
01:18:17,812 --> 01:18:18,633
Say hello to everyone.

1138
01:18:18,673 --> 01:18:19,974
So, we've got Josh doing the camera.

1139
01:18:19,994 --> 01:18:21,175
We've got six people.

1140
01:18:21,195 --> 01:18:24,519
So, we've got two teams.

1141
01:18:25,279 --> 01:18:26,721
We set the board up earlier

1142
01:18:26,861 --> 01:18:29,463
so that they started playing before the session began.

1143
01:18:30,544 --> 01:18:34,328
And let me see, is it Sue, Sandy and Pat's turn currently?

1144
01:18:34,788 --> 01:18:35,149
All right.

1145
01:18:35,649 --> 01:18:37,811
So, would you like to, they are playing

1146
01:18:37,871 --> 01:18:40,614
as the dinosaur kangaroo object.

1147
01:18:41,497 --> 01:18:45,039
At the beginning of the game you get to decorate your piece so that it becomes more like you.

1148
01:18:45,239 --> 01:18:46,719
With edible pens of course.

1149
01:18:46,899 --> 01:18:49,140
The pieces are, the whole board is entirely edible.

1150
01:18:49,980 --> 01:18:56,263
So they are moving and they're going to land on top of the candy corn.

1151
01:18:57,103 --> 01:18:59,684
So we can see on the side there's a little legend.

1152
01:18:59,964 --> 01:19:01,825
The candy corn is number six.

1153
01:19:02,065 --> 01:19:07,227
So I pull out the sacred tomb of the oven mitt and I look up ritual number six.

1154
01:19:09,230 --> 01:19:10,851
Pick up the sacred square.

1155
01:19:11,772 --> 01:19:13,353
Now, everybody gets a sacred square.

1156
01:19:13,373 --> 01:19:15,214
So if you're playing with more than just two people,

1157
01:19:15,614 --> 01:19:17,996
people grab them from the extra supply that I have.

1158
01:19:19,437 --> 01:19:23,019
Hold sacred square high above your head with both hands.

1159
01:19:26,021 --> 01:19:27,702
Look at the sacred square.

1160
01:19:29,423 --> 01:19:29,883
Squint.

1161
01:19:30,383 --> 01:19:31,664
Squint against the grandeur.

1162
01:19:33,907 --> 01:19:36,873
Move the sacred square to your mouth with your hands.

1163
01:19:37,735 --> 01:19:39,359
Consume the sacred square.

1164
01:19:48,370 --> 01:19:52,631
So when they are done consuming, they then get to push things around on the board.

1165
01:19:52,751 --> 01:19:55,352
So hopefully we'll be able to zoom in and see what they're doing.

1166
01:19:55,693 --> 01:19:58,834
You have to push everything so it all hits up against the edge.

1167
01:19:59,734 --> 01:20:00,835
So that might move you.

1168
01:20:01,275 --> 01:20:05,436
And in this case, it's actually moved the eyes into a position where the other team

1169
01:20:05,516 --> 01:20:06,197
can reach it.

1170
01:20:06,897 --> 01:20:09,658
So I don't know, do they want the funny candy eye things?

1171
01:20:13,640 --> 01:20:14,600
Looks like they do.

1172
01:20:15,514 --> 01:20:18,677
Alright, so that is ritual number eight.

1173
01:20:19,998 --> 01:20:21,579
Alright, let me make sure I get the right one.

1174
01:20:21,680 --> 01:20:21,940
Okay.

1175
01:20:22,961 --> 01:20:24,442
Pick up the sacred square.

1176
01:20:24,462 --> 01:20:30,727
Everyone's got one.

1177
01:20:31,588 --> 01:20:32,509
Close your eyes.

1178
01:20:33,710 --> 01:20:37,453
Do a 180 degree turn so that no one will see what happens.

1179
01:20:39,936 --> 01:20:40,976
Keep your eyes closed.

1180
01:20:43,072 --> 01:20:45,655
Think of your most embarrassing memory.

1181
01:20:46,095 --> 01:20:47,797
It's not like anyone's watching you right now.

1182
01:20:50,059 --> 01:20:53,022
Place square in your mouth and consume.

1183
01:20:55,244 --> 01:20:57,286
When you are done consuming, you may turn around.

1184
01:20:58,387 --> 01:21:00,149
Keep thinking about that embarrassing moment.

1185
01:21:10,669 --> 01:21:15,194
Yay, and so now they would get to move stuff on the board if they want to finish their

1186
01:21:15,214 --> 01:21:15,514
turn.

1187
01:21:21,461 --> 01:21:22,742
You switch where they're going to push it.

1188
01:21:22,762 --> 01:21:24,344
They're going to go that way.

1189
01:21:24,364 --> 01:21:26,486
So you always have to end up on top of a square.

1190
01:21:28,128 --> 01:21:30,730
